   + std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", stale_value);
   ```
   
   This ensures the program prints the intended element without ever
   dereferencing the now‑dangling iterator.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: To prevent this entire class of iterator‑invalidating
   use‑after‑free bugs, redesign the code to avoid raw iterators that can be
   invalidated by subsequent modifications. For example, use an index or a
   size‑based snapshot:
   
   ```cpp
   size_t idx = 2;                     // store the position instead of an iterator
   for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {
       v.push_back(i);
   }
   assert(idx < v.size());
   std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", v[idx]);
   ```
   
   Alternatively, switch to a container with stable iterators (e.g.,
   `std::list`) or insert a compile‑time check that no iterator is stored across
   a potentially reallocating operation. By operating on indices or stable
   containers, the code can no longer produce dangling iterator references,
   eliminating the underlying pattern of iterator‑invalidating bugs.
